WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:17.117 --> 00:00:19.486
REPORTER (over TV):
 Is the climate in this
 country really changing?

00:00:19.486 --> 00:00:22.256
REPORTER (over TV):
 Yes, and not only in
 this country, Bill.

00:00:22.256 --> 00:00:25.325
There are many lines of
 evidence, which show that
 the climate has slowly been

00:00:25.325 --> 00:00:29.997
warming up during the
 20th century over almost
 the entire Earth's surface.

00:00:30.264 --> 00:00:33.333
REPORTER (over TV): Man
 may be unwittingly changing
 the world's climate through

00:00:33.333 --> 00:00:35.435
the waste products
 of his civilization.

00:00:35.435 --> 00:00:38.505
REPORTER (over TV): Over
 pollution unless checked
 could so warm the Earth in

00:00:38.505 --> 00:00:42.409
200 years as to
 create a greenhouse effect
 melting the Arctic ice.

00:00:43.043 --> 00:00:46.280
REPORTER (over TV): The
 temperature of the lower
 atmosphere will rise perhaps

00:00:46.280 --> 00:00:50.160
to a greater extent than
 at any time since the
 end of the last ice age.

00:00:50.180 --> 00:00:53.380
JAMES: This evidence
represents a very strong
case, in my opinion,

00:00:53.380 --> 00:00:57.700
that the greenhouse effect
has been detected and it is
changing our climate now.

00:00:57.700 --> 00:01:02.129
NARRATOR: The science is in:
 for decades, there's been
 scientific consensus that

00:01:02.129 --> 00:01:08.100
climate change is real, is
 caused by humans and poses
 a threat to civilization.

00:01:08.200 --> 00:01:13.900
CARL: Solving these problems
requires a transnational

00:01:14.040 --> 00:01:17.960
and transgenerational
perspective.

00:01:18.120 --> 00:01:22.060
NARRATOR: Starting at the
 United Nations Earth Summit
 in Rio de Janeiro in 1992,

00:01:22.583 --> 00:01:25.552
the international
 community began working
 together to address the

00:01:25.552 --> 00:01:27.880
greatest issue
 in human history.

00:01:28.200 --> 00:01:32.000
REPORTER (over TV): 175
 nations did sign a blueprint
 for the world's future.

00:01:32.392 --> 00:01:34.194
It's a weaker
 blueprint than many wanted,

00:01:34.194 --> 00:01:37.097
but the real test comes
 in the months and years ahead.

00:01:37.360 --> 00:01:41.400
NARRATOR: Every year since
 1995, the global community
 has gathered together

00:01:41.740 --> 00:01:45.160
to negotiate a lasting
 agreement to reduce
 carbon emissions.

00:01:45.900 --> 00:01:48.560
REPORTER (over TV):
 In Japan today, talks
 on a global climate

00:01:48.575 --> 00:01:51.411
treaty went
 way into overtime.

00:01:51.411 --> 00:01:54.381
REPORTER (over TV): The
 ink is barely dry on an
 historic agreement to fight

00:01:54.381 --> 00:01:57.617
global warming and
 already its future is in doubt.

00:01:57.617 --> 00:01:59.386
REPORTER (over TV):
 Big polluters like India

00:01:59.386 --> 00:02:01.521
and China haven't signed on.

00:02:01.521 --> 00:02:05.625
NARRATOR: Despite the failings
 of international climate
 negotiations and agreements,

00:02:05.625 --> 00:02:10.980
advocates from cities,
 towns and states, along with
 businesses and universities,

00:02:11.260 --> 00:02:13.420
continued their pressure.

00:02:13.433 --> 00:02:15.435
REPORTER (over TV): Hundreds
 of thousands took to the
 streets of New York today.

00:02:15.435 --> 00:02:17.671
NARRATOR: And renewable
 energy continued to grow.

00:02:17.938 --> 00:02:21.274
REPORTER (over TV): You may
 want to consider a job in
 the clean energy industry.

00:02:21.274 --> 00:02:23.610
It is growing and
 they need more workers.

00:02:23.610 --> 00:02:27.547
NARRATOR: And in 2015,
 led by the world's largest
 carbon emitters,

00:02:28.220 --> 00:02:30.280
the world came
 together in Paris.

00:02:31.560 --> 00:02:34.120
REPORTER (over TV): It
 took two decades, but now a
 historic agreement on climate

00:02:34.287 --> 00:02:37.120
change signed by nearly
 every nation in the world.

00:02:37.691 --> 00:02:39.726
(speaking in
foreign language).

00:02:39.726 --> 00:02:42.529
REPORTER (over TV): We've
 written a new chapter
 of hope in the lives of

00:02:42.529 --> 00:02:44.364
7 billion
 people on the planet.

00:02:44.364 --> 00:02:46.400
REPORTER (over TV):
 The new deal will not
 end global warming,

00:02:46.400 --> 00:02:49.269
but signatories
 have agreed to reduce
 their carbon emissions

00:02:49.269 --> 00:02:51.271
and it's being
 seen as a turning point.

00:02:51.605 --> 00:02:54.474
PRESIDENT OBAMA: The
Paris Agreement represents
the best chance we've had

00:02:54.474 --> 00:02:56.543
to save the one
planet that we've got.

00:02:56.543 --> 00:02:59.279
(applause).

00:03:12.300 --> 00:03:16.740
PRESIDENT TRUMP: In
order to fulfill my solemn
duty to protect America

00:03:16.820 --> 00:03:21.900
and its citizens, the
United States will withdraw

00:03:24.440 --> 00:03:28.680
from the Paris Climate Accord.

00:03:31.311 --> 00:03:37.184
I was elected to
represent the citizens of
Pittsburgh, not Paris.

00:03:47.260 --> 00:03:50.030
PEDUTO: It's the afternoon.
I'm sitting in this room.

00:03:50.030 --> 00:03:56.020
I'm looking over my
phone and I get an alert
and the alert says,

00:03:56.260 --> 00:04:00.460
"I was elected to
represent the people of
Pittsburgh, not Paris."

00:04:01.775 --> 00:04:03.310
PRESIDENT TRUMP: Thank you.

00:04:03.310 --> 00:04:05.045
PEDUTO: Read it twice.

00:04:05.045 --> 00:04:07.881
Went into to my chief of
staff's office and just
yelled, "Pittsburgh?!"

00:04:07.881 --> 00:04:09.883
And he's like, what
are you talking about?

00:04:09.883 --> 00:04:11.384
And I said,

00:04:12.352 --> 00:04:15.455
and I started tweeting back
that Pittsburgh was going

00:04:15.455 --> 00:04:18.291
to stay in the
Paris Agreement.

00:04:19.059 --> 00:04:21.194
(inaudible).

00:04:21.194 --> 00:04:24.498
EVA: In the aftermath of
President Trump pulling out of
the Paris Climate Agreement,

00:04:24.498 --> 00:04:28.902
Pittsburghers came out in
thousands to say that we were
going to take climate action

00:04:28.902 --> 00:04:32.239
into our own hands and
move forward as a city.

00:04:32.572 --> 00:04:37.611
PEDUTO: And so we
decided to show how policy
at a local level will help

00:04:37.611 --> 00:04:39.780
to change the world.

00:04:39.780 --> 00:04:42.349
REPORTER (over TV): Mayor
 Bill Peduto signed an executive
 order today that requires

00:04:42.349 --> 00:04:45.085
the city to follow
 the guidelines of
 the Paris Agreement.

00:04:45.085 --> 00:04:47.687
NARRATOR: It wasn't just
 Pittsburgh that reacted
 to this announcement.

00:04:48.588 --> 00:04:51.792
A movement was galvanized
 around the country.

00:04:51.792 --> 00:04:54.694
REPORTER (over TV): Already
 this morning there is a new
 drive that's gaining steam to

00:04:54.700 --> 00:04:59.180
stick to the U.S.'s
 commitments combating climate
 change despite President Trump.

00:04:59.300 --> 00:05:03.780
NARRATOR: In the U.S.,
 hundreds of cities, states,
 universities and businesses

00:05:04.304 --> 00:05:07.440
joined the ranks of
 those already committed
 to the goals of Paris.

00:05:08.275 --> 00:05:13.713
BROWN: Mayors and governors,
we're here in the action on
the field taking the kind of

00:05:13.713 --> 00:05:18.718
steps that are needed
to get the job done to
preserve our climate.

00:05:18.718 --> 00:05:22.822
NARRATOR: A revolution is
 underway to tackle our biggest
 sources of carbon emissions,

00:05:23.256 --> 00:05:27.127
creating transformations
 in how people get
 around, build buildings,

00:05:27.127 --> 00:05:30.797
grow food and
 generate electricity.

00:05:30.797 --> 00:05:35.302
So while coal plants
 continue to close, clean
 energy is creating jobs,

00:05:35.669 --> 00:05:38.305
growing the economy
 and lowering emissions.

00:05:38.672 --> 00:05:41.341
PEDUTO: Despite the
President's announcement,

00:05:41.341 --> 00:05:44.911
we are still moving
ahead in renewable energy.

00:05:44.920 --> 00:05:51.400
There are now more jobs in
renewable energy in the state
of Pennsylvania than coal,

00:05:51.960 --> 00:05:55.340
natural gas and oil combined.

00:05:55.822 --> 00:05:58.458
CURBELO: I think the
president has it wrong.

00:05:58.458 --> 00:06:02.162
This isn't a zero-sum
game where we either
save the environment

00:06:02.162 --> 00:06:04.698
or grow the economy.

00:06:04.698 --> 00:06:07.968
We can do both
at the same time.

00:06:07.968 --> 00:06:11.605
BLOOMBERG: The American
government may have pulled
out of the Paris Agreement,

00:06:11.605 --> 00:06:16.977
but the American people are
committed to its goals and
there is nothing Washington

00:06:16.977 --> 00:06:19.980
can do to stop us.

00:06:19.980 --> 00:06:23.617
NARRATOR: The solutions
 are at hand and it
 couldn't be soon enough.

00:06:23.617 --> 00:06:26.953
The front lines of
 climate change are now
 in everyone's backyard,

00:06:26.953 --> 00:06:29.656
from California to
 Iowa to Florida.

00:06:29.656 --> 00:06:34.894
Climate change is not
 coming, it's already here.

00:06:43.903 --> 00:06:47.574
CASTRO: I grew up in the
heart of South Miami and
when I was 10 years old,

00:06:47.574 --> 00:06:50.543
I first started to get
involved in surfing.

00:06:54.014 --> 00:06:58.551
I remember coming out
on South Beach early on when I
started to surf and I remember

00:06:58.551 --> 00:07:04.658
just seeing vast land of
sand before you hit the beach
and now you know I come back

00:07:04.658 --> 00:07:10.730
to Miami and I continue to be
shocked at how close the water
is encroaching on South Beach.

00:07:10.730 --> 00:07:14.901
I think we're going
to have to adapt very, very
quickly to the rising tides

00:07:14.901 --> 00:07:16.736
and to the rising seas.

00:07:16.736 --> 00:07:19.539
CLEETUS: Climate
change isn't just about
some far-off future.

00:07:19.539 --> 00:07:21.708
It's actually happening
all around us right now.

00:07:21.708 --> 00:07:25.578
And here in the U.S.
along the east and Gulf coast

00:07:25.578 --> 00:07:28.081
of the country in particular,
we have some real hotspots

00:07:28.081 --> 00:07:31.785
where we're seeing
even greater and faster
rates of sea level rise.

00:07:32.585 --> 00:07:37.023
MANN: In Florida, there isn't
much elevation and so they
are now dealing with perennial

00:07:37.023 --> 00:07:41.540
flooding in Miami Beach,
in Fort Lauderdale, from
what they call king tides.

00:07:41.600 --> 00:07:44.798
REPORTER (over TV):
 King tides are here and the
 rising floodwaters are creating

00:07:44.798 --> 00:07:46.966
some trouble for
 drivers and residents.

00:07:46.966 --> 00:07:49.936
REPORTER (over TV): Salt
 water seeping up through storm
 drains and over the sea wall,

00:07:49.936 --> 00:07:52.639
soaking the streets
 of Miami Beach.

00:07:52.639 --> 00:07:57.777
MANN: These are seasonal high
tides that have been there for
the eons and yet now when they

00:07:57.777 --> 00:08:00.880
arrive in the fall they flood
the streets of Miami Beach,

00:08:01.481 --> 00:08:03.717
and that's because
of sea level rise.

00:08:03.717 --> 00:08:07.754
CASTRO: In fact, there is an
image of an octopus that was
found in a parking garage half

00:08:07.754 --> 00:08:11.958
mile in from the beach
and it's just showing that,
you know, this is real deal.

00:08:12.800 --> 00:08:17.180
LEWIS: The big focus in
Miami Beach, I believe,
is on adaptation.

00:08:17.460 --> 00:08:22.836
They're spending
$500,000,000 on pumps to
keep the tidal water off

00:08:22.836 --> 00:08:24.904
the streets
during king tides.

00:08:24.904 --> 00:08:28.808
So, you adapt to climate
change by elevating roads,

00:08:28.808 --> 00:08:30.677
putting that green
infrastructure in,

00:08:30.677 --> 00:08:33.146
slowing the worse
effects from happening.

00:08:33.146 --> 00:08:38.520
So that's getting a lot
of attention because
people see that as,

00:08:38.620 --> 00:08:41.780
keep the water away
from me kind of thing.

00:08:43.320 --> 00:08:48.320
What they're not doing quick
enough is addressing things
like salt water intrusion and

00:08:48.328 --> 00:08:53.600
when people talk about sea
level rise being the thing
that gets us out of here

00:08:53.600 --> 00:08:58.772
because we're flooding,
I wonder if it couldn't be
freshwater vulnerability that

00:08:58.780 --> 00:09:01.180
gets us out of here faster.

00:09:02.500 --> 00:09:05.779
NARRATOR: The Everglades
 is a critical source of
 fresh drinking water

00:09:05.779 --> 00:09:08.915
for nearly eight million
 people in southern Florida.

00:09:08.915 --> 00:09:13.853
But as the sea rises,
 it's moving inland, pushing
 sea water into the aquifers

00:09:13.853 --> 00:09:17.857
and the Everglades, and
 threatening the freshwater
 supply for the entire region.

00:09:27.934 --> 00:09:30.637
CASTRO: A lot of people,
when they think of sea level
rise in the State of Florida,

00:09:30.637 --> 00:09:34.641
they think encroaching
on the coastlines,
but because we're,

00:09:34.641 --> 00:09:36.876
we're built on
this porous limestone,

00:09:36.876 --> 00:09:40.113
water can
actually percolate up.

00:09:40.120 --> 00:09:42.500
WANLESS: Once the water
level's up, the water
will just come through.

00:09:42.500 --> 00:09:44.160
CASTRO: Come through, right.

00:09:44.160 --> 00:09:46.920
WANLESS: And there's
essentially nothing we
can do to stop that.

00:09:47.960 --> 00:09:50.890
That's a real problem
because as sea level has risen,

00:09:50.890 --> 00:09:53.893
we've been pulling
harder on wells,

00:09:53.893 --> 00:09:58.565
sucking harder, so we're
sort of pulling salt water in
from the ocean too, doing that.

00:09:59.399 --> 00:10:01.968
CASTRO: It's almost,
we're pulling up brackish
water, essentially.

00:10:01.968 --> 00:10:05.738
WANLESS: Yes, we've had
to move the wells farther
and farther inland.

00:10:05.738 --> 00:10:09.576
I think probably within
the next 30 years we'll
have lost our fresh water

00:10:09.976 --> 00:10:13.012
in South Florida.

00:10:13.513 --> 00:10:15.915
MANN: Look at global
sea level rise.

00:10:15.915 --> 00:10:18.852
Here's another area
of the science where,
as we learn more,

00:10:18.852 --> 00:10:21.754
we're discovering that we may
be worse off than we thought,

00:10:22.155 --> 00:10:26.059
the models may have under
predicted the amount of sea
level rise that we could see

00:10:26.593 --> 00:10:28.995
by just the
end of this century.

00:10:28.995 --> 00:10:31.197
If you look at even
a recent report of the

00:10:31.197 --> 00:10:33.766
Intergovernmental
Panel on Climate Change,

00:10:33.766 --> 00:10:36.002
they were looking at
a worst-case scenario
of a little more than

00:10:36.002 --> 00:10:40.260
three feet of sea level
rise by the end of
the century, globally.

00:10:41.207 --> 00:10:45.240
But now there's enough new
science that's come in that
tells us that the ice sheets

00:10:45.245 --> 00:10:49.048
are losing ice faster, that
there are processes that
we didn't have in our models

00:10:49.048 --> 00:10:52.919
and as we put them
into the models, we're now
learning that we could be in

00:10:52.919 --> 00:10:57.123
for more than six feet
of global sea level rise
by the end of the century.

00:11:00.760 --> 00:11:02.929
Even if we stop emitting
carbon to the atmosphere now,

00:11:03.296 --> 00:11:05.131
just because of the
inertia of the system,

00:11:05.131 --> 00:11:08.868
we will continue to see
sea level rise for some time.

00:11:08.868 --> 00:11:11.905
And if we continue with
business as usual, if we
don't do anything about our

00:11:11.905 --> 00:11:16.910
escalating carbon emissions,
there is nothing to prevent
us from melting most of the

00:11:17.977 --> 00:11:21.114
West Antarctic ice sheet
and a large part of the
Greenland ice sheet.

00:11:22.482 --> 00:11:27.220
And if we go down that
path then at some point in
the future we could be seeing

00:11:27.787 --> 00:11:31.658
20 feet of
global sea level rise.

00:11:35.995 --> 00:11:38.798
LUBBER: It's not
happening ten years from
now, it is happening now.

00:11:39.165 --> 00:11:42.669
Floods are devastating
communities, are
devastating economies,

00:11:43.736 --> 00:11:46.172
are taking away
people's homes.

00:11:46.172 --> 00:11:47.807
Think about Miami Beach.

00:11:47.807 --> 00:11:49.976
We're still seeing
building in those areas.

00:11:49.976 --> 00:11:54.080
People want to live on the
waterfront, but the economic
signals are very clear.

00:11:54.080 --> 00:11:59.580
Insurance companies don't want
to insure those places, uh,
they're being redlined out,

00:11:59.600 --> 00:12:03.756
meaning they're allowing
people to fend for themselves
or they're raising their

00:12:03.756 --> 00:12:07.093
prices so high that you
can't even get insurance.

00:12:07.093 --> 00:12:10.096
NARRATOR: In the U.S.,
 it's estimated that
 in about 25 years,

00:12:10.096 --> 00:12:13.967
more than 300,000 homes
 and businesses valued

00:12:13.967 --> 00:12:18.360
at $135 billion may be
 chronically flooded.

00:12:18.880 --> 00:12:23.060
And by the end of the
 century, that number grows
 to two and a half million.

00:12:23.710 --> 00:12:26.379
ROS-LEHTINEN: I represent
communities that people
would think they're pretty

00:12:26.380 --> 00:12:33.300
conservative and yet now
that they see the impact, the
economic impact that sea level

00:12:33.380 --> 00:12:38.980
rise and climate change has
on their pocketbooks and the
revenues that their cities

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:44.320
bring in, they're
understanding that this
is a conservative issue.

00:12:44.640 --> 00:12:51.020
But many Republican
public officials do not see
the urgency in this because

00:12:51.404 --> 00:12:55.074
it has been a partisan
issue for a long time.

00:12:55.074 --> 00:12:59.145
INHOFE: When you say that
science is settled and the
overwhelming scientific

00:12:59.145 --> 00:13:02.815
analysis comes to that
conclusion, frankly that
is just not correct.

00:13:03.583 --> 00:13:07.086
CRUZ: Climate change is
not science, it's religion.

00:13:07.086 --> 00:13:10.223
CLEETUS: Climate denialism,
the sort of anti-science
attitude about what is

00:13:10.857 --> 00:13:14.761
clearly observable and
which has been supported
by multiple lines of evidence

00:13:15.828 --> 00:13:19.032
didn't happen by accident.

00:13:19.365 --> 00:13:23.236
There has been a very
well-funded, long-standing
fossil fuel lobby that has

00:13:23.236 --> 00:13:27.040
been spreading disinformation
and trying to undercut any

00:13:27.040 --> 00:13:30.209
attempt at climate
action in the U.S.

00:13:30.443 --> 00:13:34.881
GERRARD: To this day, Koch
Industries, a privately-owned
fossil fuel company,

00:13:35.682 --> 00:13:38.918
have been funding
climate denial activities,

00:13:39.619 --> 00:13:43.956
have been working
as hard as they can to
fight climate regulation.

00:13:43.956 --> 00:13:46.459
REPORTER (over TV): The
 Koch brothers are among
 the nation's best-known

00:13:46.459 --> 00:13:48.461
politically active families.

00:13:48.461 --> 00:13:51.297
The billionaires'
 network of political action
 committees and advocacy groups

00:13:51.297 --> 00:13:56.202
will spend $300,000,000
 on campaign 2016.

00:13:56.202 --> 00:14:00.306
TAYLOR: Most Republicans
in the House and the Senate
privately understand full well

00:14:00.306 --> 00:14:03.810
climate change is real,
it's not this fiction,
it's not a scam,

00:14:04.300 --> 00:14:08.320
it's not concocted by
liberal activists trying
to destroy capitalism.

00:14:08.440 --> 00:14:12.980
Uh, that it's a
dangerous thing, that we're
seeing its impacts now.

00:14:12.985 --> 00:14:15.121
They're afraid of what it's
going to mean for the future.

00:14:15.121 --> 00:14:18.257
They just don't know exactly
what they can do about it
politically that won't cost

00:14:18.257 --> 00:14:22.161
them their job
through a primary challenge.

00:14:22.161 --> 00:14:25.098
GERRARD: Climate denial
is not limited to
the federal government.

00:14:25.098 --> 00:14:28.234
Some governors have engaged
in some similar activities.

00:14:28.501 --> 00:14:30.903
Governor Rick Scott
of Florida, for example.

00:14:30.903 --> 00:14:33.005
REPORTER (over TV):
 State's Department of
 Environmental Protection

00:14:33.005 --> 00:14:36.175
banned some employees
 from using the term climate
 change or global warming.

00:14:36.476 --> 00:14:38.344
This unwritten policy
 went into effect after

00:14:38.344 --> 00:14:41.013
Republican Governor
 Rick Scott took office.

00:14:41.013 --> 00:14:44.484
GERRARD: It's almost
as if President Trump
is following Governor Scott

00:14:44.484 --> 00:14:47.987
and adopting the
same kinds of tactics.

00:14:47.987 --> 00:14:52.191
Almost all of his
cabinet members have been
out front in denying that

00:14:52.191 --> 00:14:55.294
climate change
is being caused mostly
by human activities.

00:14:56.095 --> 00:14:58.197
PRUITT: Thank you
Mr. President.

00:14:58.200 --> 00:15:04.120
Your decision today to exit
the Paris Accord reflects
your unflinching commitment

00:15:04.260 --> 00:15:06.200
to put America first.

00:15:06.205 --> 00:15:08.441
GERRARD: They have been
going through various
federal documents

00:15:08.441 --> 00:15:11.377
and x-ing out the
terms "climate change."

00:15:12.044 --> 00:15:16.149
They want to slash the
budgets of the scientific
research agencies.

00:15:16.149 --> 00:15:18.384
In every imaginable way,

00:15:18.384 --> 00:15:22.121
the administration has been
discouraging the use of science.

00:15:22.121 --> 00:15:25.725
ROS-LEHTINEN: It's hard
for us to move any kind of
legislation because if we have

00:15:25.725 --> 00:15:29.162
the administration against us,
it's just really difficult.

00:15:29.896 --> 00:15:35.301
SUH: This administration
clearly has the environment in
its bull's-eye and is clearly,

00:15:35.835 --> 00:15:39.372
and systematically,
going after every single
environmental statute and

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:46.140
regulation as well as the
