00:16:36.262 --> 00:16:37.597
We don't have the problem.

00:16:37.597 --> 00:16:39.599
You, up in Orlando.

00:16:39.599 --> 00:16:44.070
You better set aside your
groundwater resources and
you better plan for us.

00:16:44.070 --> 00:16:46.305
You really better
plan 'cause we are coming.

00:16:46.305 --> 00:16:49.108
It's not if we don't do
something, we may be coming.

00:16:49.108 --> 00:16:51.477
We will be coming.

00:16:52.445 --> 00:16:55.314
NARRATOR: A recent
 study showed that by
 the end of the century,

00:16:55.314 --> 00:16:58.317
as many as two
 and a half million people
 from southern Florida

00:16:58.317 --> 00:17:01.420
may be displaced
 due to climate change.

00:17:01.420 --> 00:17:04.590
And many of them could
 be headed to Orlando.

00:17:08.261 --> 00:17:11.497
The city is not
 only preparing for these
 impacts of climate change,

00:17:11.497 --> 00:17:14.233
they're also doing
 their part to fight it,

00:17:14.233 --> 00:17:16.402
despite federal inaction.

00:17:16.402 --> 00:17:21.507
ISAAC: The message around
climate has been so hard for
ordinary people to plug into.

00:17:22.675 --> 00:17:26.479
It's been big and
scary and something
that's happening far away and

00:17:26.479 --> 00:17:29.515
something that I personally
can't do anything about.

00:17:30.049 --> 00:17:31.517
And that's not true.

00:17:31.517 --> 00:17:33.486
It is big and scary.

00:17:33.486 --> 00:17:36.322
But there are things
we can do and we can impact
policy in our communities

00:17:36.322 --> 00:17:38.391
that can make
a big difference.

00:17:38.658 --> 00:17:40.660
Yeah, if everybody
could take a seat.

00:17:40.660 --> 00:17:44.630
So, I want to say welcome
and thank you for being here.

00:17:44.630 --> 00:17:50.403
When we founded the First
50 Coalition, our goal was
to make our city one of the

00:17:50.970 --> 00:17:55.241
first 50 in the
nation to commit to 100%
renewable energy by 2050.

00:17:57.310 --> 00:18:01.247
DYER: A lot of greenhouse
gas emissions come from cities

00:18:01.881 --> 00:18:06.185
so after the
current administration
withdrew us from Paris,

00:18:06.485 --> 00:18:09.155
there had been a
number of cities that stepped

00:18:09.155 --> 00:18:12.358
up to the challenge on
renewables and just kind of
galvanized us at the local

00:18:12.358 --> 00:18:16.262
level that we had to pick up
the sword and charge forward.

00:18:17.063 --> 00:18:20.666
SPEAKER: Good afternoon,
I'd like to welcome
you to the August 8th meeting

00:18:20.666 --> 00:18:22.401
of the
Orlando City Council.

00:18:22.401 --> 00:18:24.704
We're going to...

00:18:24.704 --> 00:18:28.207
ISAAC: So we went to the city
council to get a commitment to
100% renewable energy by 2050;

00:18:28.674 --> 00:18:30.343
we were hopeful.

00:18:30.343 --> 00:18:33.212
Every single person in
that room was in support.

00:18:33.212 --> 00:18:36.082
I don't think that's
ever happened at a city
commission meeting before,

00:18:36.582 --> 00:18:39.585
where absolutely everybody
is in favor of something.

00:18:40.119 --> 00:18:42.555
DYER: All those
in favor of the motion
indicate so by saying aye.

00:18:42.555 --> 00:18:45.691
Those opposed, and so the
motion carries unanimously.

00:18:46.926 --> 00:18:49.228
(applause).

00:18:49.228 --> 00:18:51.063
ISAAC: And they voted yes!

00:18:51.063 --> 00:18:53.165
REPORTER (over TV):
 The City of Orlando has
 committed to running on

00:18:53.165 --> 00:18:55.568
clean renewable energy by 2050.

00:18:55.568 --> 00:18:58.637
ISAAC: And that was the
whole reason we started
is we needed a win.

00:18:58.637 --> 00:19:00.206
We need a positive momentum.

00:19:00.206 --> 00:19:03.643
We needed to say this is the
kind of community we could be.

00:19:03.643 --> 00:19:06.645
NARRATOR: Commitments to
 renewable energy are being
 made around the country.

00:19:07.146 --> 00:19:10.449
More than 75 cities
 throughout the U.S.
 have already committed

00:19:10.449 --> 00:19:14.460
to using 100% renewable
 energy by midcentury.

00:19:15.080 --> 00:19:19.320
To help make this happen
 cities are developing
 innovative solutions.

00:19:20.159 --> 00:19:23.562
CASTRO: One of the things
that we're doing in Orlando
is testing floating solar,

00:19:23.562 --> 00:19:25.731
what we call
floating voltaics.

00:19:25.731 --> 00:19:30.636
There's 9,000 man-made ponds,
that have been created to
capture storm water from the

00:19:30.636 --> 00:19:36.342
streets and we've started
to test out in some of these
ponds how to put floating

00:19:36.342 --> 00:19:38.611
solar on top of them.

00:19:38.611 --> 00:19:42.515
We've also turned
on one of the largest
installations that we have,

00:19:42.515 --> 00:19:46.719
it's a 12-megawatt
community solar farm, and
it was literally over decades

00:19:46.719 --> 00:19:51.557
a landfill where we
were turning coal ash after
being burned and burying it.

00:19:52.191 --> 00:19:54.660
And we realized that
after that was capped,

00:19:54.660 --> 00:19:58.464
that that was a prime
spot for us to put solar up.

00:19:58.464 --> 00:20:02.435
We're also transitioning
our downtown bus
rapid transit system to

00:20:02.435 --> 00:20:04.770
100% electric
zero-emission buses.

00:20:06.280 --> 00:20:10.400
Another high priority
is the energy-food nexus.

00:20:11.820 --> 00:20:15.314
We're shipping
food all around the world,
all around the country,

00:20:15.314 --> 00:20:19.285
15 to 1,800
miles per person,
per plate, per day.

00:20:20.119 --> 00:20:23.355
And in fact, people
have done research that
food systems contribute

00:20:23.360 --> 00:20:26.160
as much as a third of
global climate change.

00:20:27.700 --> 00:20:29.528
So we were like, all right,

00:20:29.528 --> 00:20:32.465
one, we need to localize it,
as local as possible.

00:20:32.731 --> 00:20:36.368
Two, we need
to use zero-emission
transportation to build,

00:20:36.368 --> 00:20:41.100
maintain and distribute that
produce to the end users,
markets and restaurants.

00:20:41.180 --> 00:20:43.580
And that's the epiphany that
we had with Fleet Farming.

00:20:44.243 --> 00:20:47.313
PERRY: So starting out,
we're going to go ahead and
have a group that's going

00:20:47.313 --> 00:20:50.316
to harvest and a group
that's going to turn a plot.

00:20:50.850 --> 00:20:56.555
CASTRO: There's 40 million
acres of lawns across this
country that are absorbing

00:20:56.555 --> 00:21:00.326
a lot of the water resources,
that we're spraying a lot of
fertilizers on and causing

00:21:00.326 --> 00:21:04.597
other problems and that
we could convert into
edible landscapes that

00:21:04.597 --> 00:21:07.500
can produce our
food in our neighborhood.

00:21:07.500 --> 00:21:09.702
Not just local
but hyper-local.

00:21:09.702 --> 00:21:12.071
PERRY: Ok so I'm going
to go ahead and show
you how to harvest.

00:21:12.071 --> 00:21:14.440
Basically, a homeowner
pays a startup fee.

00:21:14.440 --> 00:21:16.876
We farm their front
lawns with the help
of the community during

00:21:16.876 --> 00:21:18.844
our biweekly swarm rides.

00:21:18.844 --> 00:21:23.482
We ride bikes out and
we teach the community how
to farm these front lawns.

00:21:23.482 --> 00:21:25.684
CASTRO: It's a win-win
situation across the board.

00:21:25.684 --> 00:21:29.622
The homeowner who provides
the land is actually
getting all of that produce

00:21:29.889 --> 00:21:32.358
free of charge as
much as they want.

00:21:32.358 --> 00:21:35.761
The excess that's grown,
we're harvesting and
we're taking it to market.

00:21:36.595 --> 00:21:39.798
PERRY: We got some heirloom
carrots, watermelon
radishes and beets.

00:21:40.299 --> 00:21:42.101
CASTRO: Now we're scaling.

00:21:42.101 --> 00:21:45.437
We're in West Oakland,
California, we're
operating in Jacksonville,

00:21:45.437 --> 00:21:48.274
we have
two branches in Orlando,
so we're pretty excited.

00:21:49.441 --> 00:21:53.546
NARRATOR: The pioneering
 efforts in cities like Orlando
 are essential to achieving

00:21:53.546 --> 00:21:55.748
the goals of the
 Paris Climate Accord.

00:21:56.315 --> 00:22:00.553
Orlando itself is not
 only bracing for an influx of
 people from southern Florida,

00:22:01.420 --> 00:22:05.424
but because of major
 hurricanes, which devastated
 the Caribbean in 2017,

00:22:06.125 --> 00:22:09.295
refugees from U.S. territories
 have already arrived.

00:22:09.762 --> 00:22:12.831
REPORTER (over TV):
 215,000 people have
 arrived in Florida alone.

00:22:12.831 --> 00:22:15.801
Many survivors are flying to
 Orlando International Airport

00:22:16.335 --> 00:22:18.437
where there's
 a resource center.

00:22:18.437 --> 00:22:21.473
CASTRO: Since Irma and Maria,
we've seen now 300,000 people
flee to our city and

00:22:22.240 --> 00:22:27.520
that's been a big challenge
in terms of education for the
kids, putting them into schools,

00:22:27.580 --> 00:22:30.480
finding reliable,
affordable housing
for them and then of

00:22:30.480 --> 00:22:33.420
course finding them jobs
to sustain their families.

00:23:13.620 --> 00:23:19.420
LUBBER: The hurricane season
of 2017, we saw flooding that
has absolutely devastated

00:23:19.540 --> 00:23:24.200
Puerto Rico,
Houston, Texas, hundreds
of billions of dollars'

00:23:24.300 --> 00:23:27.740
worth of damage to
people's lives, their homes.

00:23:27.740 --> 00:23:30.743
REPORTER (over TV):
 Hurricane Harvey barreling
 into the Texas coastline as

00:23:30.743 --> 00:23:33.412
a category four storm
 with 130 mile-an-hour winds.

00:23:34.313 --> 00:23:36.382
REPORTER (over TV):
 It's not just a
 little bit of rain.

00:23:36.382 --> 00:23:39.885
Look at this, feet of rain
 is what we're communicating,
 not inches but feet.

00:23:39.885 --> 00:23:43.555
CLEETUS: There are now studies
that show that the extreme
rainfall that accompanied that

00:23:43.560 --> 00:23:47.440
hurricane was made
much more likely because
of climate change.

00:23:47.560 --> 00:23:50.896
MANN: Those warm ocean
temperatures meant that
there were record amounts of

00:23:50.900 --> 00:23:56.260
moisture within that storm,
moisture that was available
to produce the worst flooding

00:23:56.340 --> 00:23:59.100
event on record in
the United States.

00:23:59.240 --> 00:24:01.900
REPORTER (over TV):
 For a third brutal
 day, torrential rain,

00:24:01.907 --> 00:24:03.776
people rescued
 from flooded homes.

00:24:03.776 --> 00:24:05.878
WOMAN (over TV):
 There's water everywhere.
 We have nowhere to go.

00:24:05.878 --> 00:24:08.747
I have all my children.
 I lost everything.

00:24:08.747 --> 00:24:10.883
I have nothing but the
 clothes on my back.

00:24:10.883 --> 00:24:15.554
MANN: These storms are
now about 20% more destructive
because of the overall warming

00:24:15.554 --> 00:24:18.924
of the ocean, which thus far
is less than a degree Celsius.

00:24:19.558 --> 00:24:22.094
Imagine what two
degrees Celsius gives us.

00:24:22.094 --> 00:24:23.962
REPORTER (over TV):
 The Caribbean has just
 been getting hammered.

00:24:23.962 --> 00:24:26.432
Here's storm number
 four in just weeks.

00:24:26.865 --> 00:24:28.801
REPORTER (over TV): The winds
 are going to be devastating.

00:24:39.745 --> 00:24:42.948
CLEETUS: These types
of extreme weather events
exacerbate already existing

00:24:42.948 --> 00:24:48.754
challenges so in the case of
Puerto Rico the electricity
grid had been under-invested

00:24:48.754 --> 00:24:50.622
in for a very long
period of time.

00:24:50.622 --> 00:24:53.459
And then this hurricane
came along and pretty
much decimated it.

00:24:54.626 --> 00:24:59.131
And that meant not just
that people lost power
but when they lost power,

00:24:59.131 --> 00:25:01.934
people lost lives.

00:25:01.934 --> 00:25:05.604
NARRATOR: Puerto Rican
 officials originally put
 the death toll at 64.

00:25:05.938 --> 00:25:10.976
But nearly a year later,
 raised that estimate to
 almost 3,000 people when

00:25:10.976 --> 00:25:14.813
accounting for the extended
 loss of electricity
 and the lack of food,

00:25:14.813 --> 00:25:18.484
water and healthcare
 after the storm.

00:25:19.518 --> 00:25:24.857
Yet in the face of tragedy,
 a remote town of 18,000 in
 the mountains of Puerto Rico,

00:25:25.491 --> 00:25:28.861
showed how renewable energy
 can be a life-saving solution.

00:25:54.019 --> 00:25:56.789
DEYA: Casa Pueblo is a
community-based organization.

00:25:57.356 --> 00:26:01.527
We're actively working
to change our energy
landscape in Adjuntas.

00:26:02.960 --> 00:26:06.800
Everything in Casa Pueblo
runs on clean energy.

00:26:06.960 --> 00:26:11.420
The radio, the production
of our brand of coffee.

00:26:11.560 --> 00:26:15.380
We have cinema theater
run on solar power.

00:26:15.480 --> 00:26:21.760
So our installation
from being, let's say
10% solar power in 1999

00:26:21.880 --> 00:26:24.680
now is fully solar power.

00:26:28.720 --> 00:26:33.600
After the hurricane,
the whole energy system
collapsed in Puerto Rico,

00:26:33.720 --> 00:26:35.720
but not in Casa Pueblo.

00:26:35.720 --> 00:26:41.300
In Casa Pueblo we opened
right away and it was
used as an energy oasis.

00:26:47.080 --> 00:26:51.780
MARTINEZ-SANCHO:
Everyone saw Casa Pueblo
as the place to look for help

00:26:52.911 --> 00:26:56.014
because power was
not anywhere around.

00:26:57.216 --> 00:27:03.021
I remember coming
to Casa Pueblo and see how
many people will do the line

00:27:03.021 --> 00:27:06.091
for the solar lamps.

00:27:06.100 --> 00:27:11.940
At least we could give
them an option, a space,
to solve their problems.

00:27:14.100 --> 00:27:19.780
DEYA: If you look around, most
of the suffering is related
to the energy component:

00:27:21.707 --> 00:27:25.110
food storage, medicine,
medical treatment,

00:27:25.944 --> 00:27:32.718
so we decided to do the solar
urgency system for 10 houses,

00:27:32.718 --> 00:27:36.889
with special needs, to
give a small solar system and

00:27:36.889 --> 00:27:40.759
enough energy to run
special equipment like
the dialysis machine

00:27:40.759 --> 00:27:43.128
or the respiratory machine.

00:27:43.128 --> 00:27:47.000
And that's Maria's house.

00:29:04.200 --> 00:29:08.040
DEYA: In Puerto Rico,
we have to move away
from fossil fuel because

00:29:08.540 --> 00:29:12.420
it's damaging our island,
our nature and others.

00:29:12.680 --> 00:29:17.060
So we are pushing for
energy self-sufficiency
for the country,

00:29:17.680 --> 00:29:23.560
but in order to do that,
the first level is to reach
that goal, at a local level,

00:29:24.020 --> 00:29:30.100
at a community level, to build
from the bottom up and to
teach others in other parts of

00:29:30.102 --> 00:29:36.208
Puerto Rico that we can
free our self by engaging
in these alternative

00:29:36.208 --> 00:29:38.777
that are within our reach.

00:29:40.040 --> 00:29:43.920
LOCKE: Renewable energy
is a core strategy for
building resilience right now

00:29:44.040 --> 00:29:46.280
in the Caribbean.

00:29:46.284 --> 00:29:49.087
I think it's in every circle
of conversation and dialogue,
whether you be at the highest

00:29:49.087 --> 00:29:52.090
levels of government or at
the local community level.

00:29:52.090 --> 00:29:56.261
And so several islands
including the Virgin Islands,
Dominica and many others are

00:29:56.261 --> 00:30:02.034
using the recent hurricanes
in the Caribbean as a catalyst
for replacing 20-century

00:30:02.040 --> 00:30:06.280
fossil fuel grids with
21st century renewable grids.

00:30:06.600 --> 00:30:10.900
These islands do not want
to be referred to as the
victims of climate change

00:30:10.900 --> 00:30:15.040
and instead are really the
ones bold enough to
provide the solutions.

00:30:15.920 --> 00:30:20.052
NARRATOR: Although Caribbean
 countries and other small
 island nations collectively

00:30:20.052 --> 00:30:25.891
produce less than 1% of
 global greenhouse gases, some
 are an important testing ground

00:30:25.891 --> 00:30:28.293
and a model for the
 future of clean energy.

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:34.360
Scientists say that we
 must scale up renewables
 to meet the Paris targets.

00:30:34.840 --> 00:30:39.820
But how fast we must act,
 and what technologies we use,
 are the critical questions.

00:30:40.080 --> 00:30:45.077
TAYLOR: We have to reduce the
global consumption of fossil
fuels by about 80% by the year

00:30:45.077 --> 00:30:49.247
2050 and completely
remove them from
the global economy only

00:30:49.748 --> 00:30:51.650
a couple of
decades thereafter.

00:30:51.650 --> 00:30:56.321
And then figure a way
to get greenhouse gases
out of the atmosphere.

00:30:56.755 --> 00:30:58.857
That is a huge challenge.

00:30:58.860 --> 00:31:02.700
ROBERTS: If you map out
what it's going to take
to hit those targets,

00:31:03.020 --> 00:31:07.460
you basically have
two broad choices and which
of those choices you choose

00:31:07.466 --> 00:31:10.335
probably depends on
who's making your model.

00:31:10.335 --> 00:31:12.037
If you're an oil company,

00:31:12.037 --> 00:31:15.006
like Shell for
instance just came out
with a scenario that shows

00:31:15.006 --> 00:31:20.178
in the short term continued
rise in fossil fuels and then

00:31:20.178 --> 00:31:23.281
around mid-century
this plunge in
emissions and then,

00:31:23.281 --> 00:31:26.685
the crucial bit, in the
latter half of the century,

00:31:26.685 --> 00:31:31.022
implementing technologies
which will involve capturing
and burying megatons of

00:31:31.022 --> 00:31:35.360
carbon, what they
call negative emissions.

00:31:35.360 --> 00:31:41.967
But maybe we shouldn't bet
the future of the human race
on a gigantic mega-project

00:31:41.967 --> 00:31:45.137
that we have not started
and do not know if we can do.

00:31:46.138 --> 00:31:48.974
Maybe that's
not a good gamble.

00:31:48.974 --> 00:31:52.177
But if you look at
the scenarios that show us
hitting our targets without

00:31:52.177 --> 00:31:56.381
negative emissions,
it involves in the short
term a very substantial,

00:31:56.915 --> 00:32:01.219
rapid decline in carbon
emissions, which means
you've got to start

00:32:01.219 --> 00:32:04.089
deploying the technology
you have as fast as possible.

00:32:05.560 --> 00:32:11.920
MANN: So we need to be putting
our foot on the renewable
energy acceleration pedal

00:32:12.020 --> 00:32:16.580
because if we can act at the
municipal level, at the city
level, at the state level,

00:32:16.740 --> 00:32:22.540
then we can actually make a
sizeable contribution towards
reducing our carbon emissions.

00:32:22.680 --> 00:32:27.920
NARRATOR: Renewable energy
 is being embraced as a real
 alternative to fossil fuels.

00:32:27.940 --> 00:32:34.540
As their costs plummet,
 the movement continues
