Training Coordinator
for Grid Alternatives,

01:04:28.131 --> 01:04:29.966
Greater Los Angeles.

01:04:29.966 --> 01:04:31.968
Salvador,
what's goin' on, man?

01:04:31.968 --> 01:04:35.004
KADISH: Our mission
is to bring the benefits of
renewable energy technology

01:04:35.004 --> 01:04:36.673
to underserved communities.

01:04:36.673 --> 01:04:39.342
We're able to have
people from the very
communities we serve,

01:04:39.342 --> 01:04:42.846
come out and get job
training on the
installations themselves.

01:04:43.780 --> 01:04:47.984
I've worked with people
who have come from prison
and within, you know,

01:04:47.984 --> 01:04:51.140
a year or two, are in
a management position at a
residential solar company.

01:04:51.580 --> 01:04:54.860
You know, they're going
from incarceration into
being entrepreneurs.

01:04:55.291 --> 01:04:57.193
-There's going to be
a lot to learn today.

01:04:57.193 --> 01:04:59.996
We are going to be on sort
of a steep pitched roof.

01:04:59.996 --> 01:05:02.132
So we definitely want
to go at a safe pace.

01:05:02.132 --> 01:05:04.300
When in doubt, ask.

01:05:04.300 --> 01:05:08.171
ANDRADE: Last year we
placed 87 individuals
in solar careers.

01:05:08.171 --> 01:05:11.274
And honestly, they're
dedicated because like
myself, once I got released,

01:05:11.541 --> 01:05:13.143
I want to stay
out of trouble.

01:05:13.143 --> 01:05:14.444
I just want to work.

01:05:14.444 --> 01:05:16.379
I've been out of
prison five years.

01:05:16.379 --> 01:05:19.215
And now everything
I do is for my son.

01:05:20.717 --> 01:05:23.453
I want him
to have everything I
didn't have in life.

01:05:23.453 --> 01:05:25.889
I want him to have it.

01:05:26.256 --> 01:05:30.160
FABER-O'CONNOR: In
LA alone we have created
29,000 green jobs.

01:05:30.560 --> 01:05:33.997
Over 80,000 solar
jobs in the state.

01:05:34.464 --> 01:05:36.366
There's such a
big opportunity.

01:05:36.366 --> 01:05:38.968
We're not afraid of
this being a job killer.

01:05:38.968 --> 01:05:43.039
This is a job creator
and people are coming to
Los Angeles, to California,

01:05:43.339 --> 01:05:45.308
to be part of that revolution.

01:05:46.676 --> 01:05:50.747
BROWN: With Trump saying he's
going to pull out of Paris,
the next best thing is for

01:05:50.747 --> 01:05:55.418
states to take their
own action because the
climate is changing,

01:05:56.085 --> 01:06:01.391
there's real impacts in
real time and this is an
existential threat to the

01:06:01.391 --> 01:06:04.494
wellbeing of everyone
everywhere in the world.

01:06:05.061 --> 01:06:07.430
NARRATOR: Since
 the announcement to
 withdraw from Paris,

01:06:07.430 --> 01:06:11.301
states and governors around
 the country have passed
 legislation to join the

01:06:11.301 --> 01:06:15.071
U.S. climate alliance and
 uphold the commitments of
 the Paris Climate Accord.

01:06:16.606 --> 01:06:20.109
New Jersey recently introduced
 a bill to join the alliance,

01:06:20.109 --> 01:06:24.247
which would bring
 its membership to 16
 states plus Puerto Rico.

01:06:24.247 --> 01:06:28.084
MUKHERJI: Mr. Speaker,
this bill if passed
and signed into law will

01:06:28.084 --> 01:06:30.353
help protect
generations to come.

01:06:30.353 --> 01:06:33.122
MR. SPEAKER: Madam clerk
open the machine for a vote.

01:06:36.359 --> 01:06:39.562
Senate bill 598 having
received 49 votes
in the affirmative,

01:06:39.562 --> 01:06:43.132
23 votes in the negative
and zero abstentions, I
declare the bill passed.

01:06:43.399 --> 01:06:46.536
Let the bill take the
usual course of passed bills.

01:06:46.536 --> 01:06:49.572
NARRATOR: New Jersey's
 decision to join the
 U.S. Climate Alliance

01:06:49.572 --> 01:06:53.343
was successful
 due to a change in
 New Jersey's leadership.

01:06:53.343 --> 01:06:56.646
POTOSNAK: Right up there
with California and New York,
New Jersey's probably on target

01:06:56.646 --> 01:06:58.514
to be the greenest
state in America.

01:06:58.514 --> 01:07:00.316
And that happened
in just one election.

01:07:00.316 --> 01:07:02.118
MURPHY: So help me God.

01:07:02.118 --> 01:07:04.487
POTOSNAK: The difference
between our new
governor, Phil Murphy,

01:07:04.487 --> 01:07:07.156
and Governor Chris Christie
couldn't be more clear.

01:07:07.490 --> 01:07:10.093
It's like night and day.

01:07:10.660 --> 01:07:15.331
Following Hurricane Sandy,
what we saw from Governor
Christie was just ignoring the

01:07:15.331 --> 01:07:19.302
causes of climate
change and ignoring
things that we can do

01:07:19.302 --> 01:07:21.504
to be more resilient
with natural systems.

01:07:21.504 --> 01:07:23.172
CHRISTIE: It's not a crisis.

01:07:23.172 --> 01:07:26.075
The climate's been
changing forever and
it will always change.

01:07:26.075 --> 01:07:28.511
POTOSNAK: It was
disappointing, but
it was also wrong,

01:07:28.511 --> 01:07:31.848
but I can tell
you for a fact the people
here in New Jersey,

01:07:31.848 --> 01:07:35.184
they understand
the connection.

01:07:35.184 --> 01:07:38.288
We were very, very
focused on making sure
the next governor,

01:07:38.288 --> 01:07:40.323
whoever was
going to be elected,

01:07:40.323 --> 01:07:45.161
was going to really
have strong plans to reduce
greenhouse gas emissions.

01:07:45.161 --> 01:07:49.132
MURPHY: A stronger and fairer
New Jersey accepts the sad
reality of climate change

01:07:49.465 --> 01:07:54.270
and invests aggressively
in renewable energy
and it upholds the goals

01:07:54.570 --> 01:07:56.873
of the
Paris Climate Accord.

01:07:56.873 --> 01:07:59.208
POTOSNAK: Since Governor
Murphy has come into office,

01:07:59.208 --> 01:08:02.512
we saw a whirlwind
of action in a very
short period of time.

01:08:02.979 --> 01:08:06.182
And I think we can take
it a step further, because
setting the bar with Paris

01:08:06.182 --> 01:08:11.554
is an important step, but
I don't think anyone who sees
a bar just wants to get there.

01:08:11.921 --> 01:08:15.491
We want to go and
reach even higher.

01:08:15.491 --> 01:08:19.562
NARRATOR: The movement that's
 working across the country
 continues to gain momentum.

01:08:19.896 --> 01:08:23.533
Since the days after the
 Trump announcement to leave
 the Paris Climate Accord,

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:28.738
the number of cities, states,
 businesses and organizations
 pledging to uphold the

01:08:28.738 --> 01:08:31.207
agreement has
 more than doubled.

01:08:31.607 --> 01:08:35.144
And with initiatives that
 are tracking the commitments
 for real change in

01:08:35.144 --> 01:08:38.581
our energy future,
 the stakes and challenges
 couldn't be clearer.

01:08:39.749 --> 01:08:44.153
But even in places
 grappling with the long
 legacy of fossil fuels,

01:08:44.153 --> 01:08:47.590
commitments to a clean energy
 future are moving forward.

01:08:48.091 --> 01:08:50.426
Regardless of
 federal inaction.

01:08:51.728 --> 01:08:56.599
PEDUTO: I couldn't disagree
with the president any
stronger and I say that as

01:08:56.600 --> 01:09:00.600
somebody who lived
through the Pittsburgh of old.

01:09:01.680 --> 01:09:05.380
Pittsburgh was the
center of heavy industry.

01:09:06.275 --> 01:09:09.679
Coal and steel became
a part of its legacy.

01:09:10.580 --> 01:09:14.550
It was a two-shirt town,
meaning that if you
worked in corporate

01:09:14.550 --> 01:09:16.753
Pittsburgh in the 1940s,

01:09:16.753 --> 01:09:20.957
you wore one shirt up
until lunchtime and then
you changed it because

01:09:20.957 --> 01:09:25.461
of the amount of soot
that would get on it.

01:09:25.461 --> 01:09:32.280
During the 50s and the 60s,
we were one of the wealthiest
cities in the United States.

01:09:33.640 --> 01:09:37.140
And then by 1979,
it all collapsed.

01:09:39.120 --> 01:09:45.420
Took 30 years between
1979 and 2009 to see
this city come back.

01:09:46.820 --> 01:09:51.660
ERVIN: The city
had to reimagine itself as
a knowledge economy where

01:09:51.988 --> 01:09:57.293
healthcare and education and
robotics really developed
and now we're starting

01:09:57.293 --> 01:09:59.328
to see the fruits
of those labors.

01:09:59.328 --> 01:10:02.532
PEDUTO: There was
a whole different part of
Pittsburgh that was thinking

01:10:02.532 --> 01:10:06.669
maybe our future doesn't
necessarily have to
be based upon the past.

01:10:08.671 --> 01:10:12.508
And these were
the people that were looking
at technology and engineering

01:10:12.508 --> 01:10:16.846
and understanding
it wasn't steel, it was
innovation that would be the

01:10:16.846 --> 01:10:22.000
cornerstone from which we
would build a new Pittsburgh.

01:10:23.480 --> 01:10:27.480
ERVIN: And now we're
in the position to reap some
of the benefits of those seeds

01:10:27.490 --> 01:10:30.593
that were sown and
create the clean economy.

01:10:30.593 --> 01:10:34.297
It's about changing
building codes, how we
plan our neighborhoods,

01:10:34.297 --> 01:10:36.732
how we design our streets.

01:10:36.740 --> 01:10:42.220
So whether you are developing
new energy-efficient housing
or you know, creating new,

01:10:42.240 --> 01:10:47.200
clean energy generation
systems, this is
economic development.

01:10:47.540 --> 01:10:50.240
This is innovation.

01:10:50.246 --> 01:10:54.817
PEDUTO: And today we are
fully committed to making
that transition to be at

01:10:54.817 --> 01:10:59.622
100% renewable energy at the
city level, a 50% reduction
in the amount of energy

01:11:00.189 --> 01:11:04.560
we're using and a zero-landfill
waste policy by 2030.

01:11:05.560 --> 01:11:09.560
It's an ambitious
goal, but it's also a
very practical goal.

01:11:13.400 --> 01:11:15.738
This city is a
city of bridges.

01:11:15.738 --> 01:11:20.443
We have more bridges
than most cities on earth.

01:11:20.443 --> 01:11:25.515
As mayor, my job is to take
all the great things that I
remember from my childhood

01:11:25.781 --> 01:11:31.554
about Pittsburgh and what it
was and make sure it gets to
the other side of the bridge

01:11:31.554 --> 01:11:36.626
and then to be able to hand
it off to somebody, because I
believe that it's not just the

01:11:36.626 --> 01:11:42.265
Pittsburghs but it's
the other cities, it's the
institutions and the youth

01:11:42.698 --> 01:11:44.433
that will help
to lead the world.

01:11:44.433 --> 01:11:46.435
PROTESTORS: Take it the polls!

01:11:46.435 --> 01:11:47.770
MAN: Take it the street!

01:11:47.770 --> 01:11:49.605
PROTESTORS: Take it the polls!

01:11:49.605 --> 01:11:52.375
IRIS: This isn't just the
beginning of one march.

01:11:52.780 --> 01:11:59.760
This is the start of us
taking control of our future.

01:12:00.620 --> 01:12:02.652
(applause).

01:12:02.652 --> 01:12:06.622
I started speaking out
because I felt like the youth
voice needed to be in the

01:12:06.622 --> 01:12:10.540
discussion about these
issues that are directly
going to impact us.

01:12:10.760 --> 01:12:17.560
And we are calling for
climate action because
this is zero hour.

01:12:17.760 --> 01:12:20.280
(cheering).

01:12:20.560 --> 01:12:25.575
This is zero hour to act
on climate change because
the clock is ticking.

01:12:25.575 --> 01:12:30.379
But when you bring together
a group of diverse young
people from all different

01:12:30.379 --> 01:12:36.519
backgrounds, we can really
come together as a movement
and take action because our

01:12:36.819 --> 01:12:39.789
lives are at stake here.

01:12:39.789 --> 01:12:42.692
EVA: I think people
in my generation and
the generation below

01:12:42.692 --> 01:12:45.161
me see this as our future.

01:12:45.161 --> 01:12:49.832
We see a viable path where
people are working and people
are installing solar panels

01:12:50.366 --> 01:12:53.836
and wind turbines and we just
see that as where we're going.

01:12:53.836 --> 01:12:55.838
It's not even a question.

01:12:55.838 --> 01:12:57.640
CASTRO: You look at the facts.

01:12:57.640 --> 01:13:01.911
The transformation
towards a renewable energy
future is the greatest

01:13:02.478 --> 01:13:05.848
economic opportunity
of the 21st century.

01:13:06.249 --> 01:13:09.919
SUH: This is
not a left state,
right state, blue state,

01:13:10.753 --> 01:13:12.755
red state issue.

01:13:12.755 --> 01:13:17.860
This is a fantastic
opportunity for communities
to revitalize themselves and

01:13:17.860 --> 01:13:20.963
combat climate change
at the exact same time.

01:13:20.963 --> 01:13:23.599
KADISH: If climate
change is going to be
addressed successfully,

01:13:23.599 --> 01:13:27.803
everyone is going to need to
participate in the solutions
and that means not just

01:13:27.803 --> 01:13:31.641
installing solar
on homes but moving people
into electric vehicles

01:13:32.341 --> 01:13:34.310
that are powered
by that solar.

01:13:34.310 --> 01:13:38.881
It means finding a way
for renters to benefit from
solar so that the gains

01:13:38.881 --> 01:13:42.018
from this new
economy flow to everybody.

01:13:42.018 --> 01:13:44.787
TAYLOR: We have to move
away from fossil fuels.

01:13:44.787 --> 01:13:49.492
One way to do that in
a fast and ambitious
fashion is to put a

01:13:49.492 --> 01:13:51.560
price on
greenhouse gas emissions.

01:13:51.560 --> 01:13:55.598
LUBBER: And it's going to take
grappling with the reality
that we need to act now.

01:13:55.598 --> 01:13:58.501
If we put it off, the
challenge gets bigger,
it gets greater.

01:13:58.501 --> 01:14:02.872
We still need scale and
having policy at a federal
level is going to be

01:14:03.406 --> 01:14:06.542
an imperative
to quicken the pace.

01:14:06.542 --> 01:14:11.547
PEDUTO: And if we look at it
as an American Marshall Plan,
and we start to build out the

01:14:11.547 --> 01:14:17.400
renewable energy industry,
we can exceed the goals
of the Paris Agreement.

01:14:17.580 --> 01:14:20.880
POTOSNAK: The minimal
thing you should be doing is
getting out there and asking

01:14:20.890 --> 01:14:24.527
candidates for office
and elected officials how
they're agreeing to tackle

01:14:24.527 --> 01:14:26.762
a big problem
like climate change.

01:14:26.762 --> 01:14:28.764
FABER-O'CONNOR: We're all
a resident of somewhere,

01:14:28.764 --> 01:14:32.601
so residents of cities
have a huge role to play.

01:14:32.601 --> 01:14:36.439
That's where we can pull
the levers on things like
transportation decisions,

01:14:36.939 --> 01:14:40.643
land use decisions, people
understanding where they
live, where they work,

01:14:40.943 --> 01:14:42.678
how they get around.

01:14:42.678 --> 01:14:45.681
This is their everyday
life that actually can
make a real difference.

01:14:45.915 --> 01:14:49.085
GARCETTI: I believe that
we will be able to bring
the best of technology,

01:14:49.085 --> 01:14:53.022
personal action, and
just the heart that
says, "this matters."

01:14:53.022 --> 01:14:56.625
Long after we're going to be
gone, that our children and
our children's children will

01:14:56.625 --> 01:15:01.597
have an earth and a quality
of life that we can feel
proud that we left behind.

01:15:01.597 --> 01:15:04.967
CLEETUS: What I'm hopeful
about is that there are so
many people around the world

01:15:04.967 --> 01:15:09.605
who are out there saying
that they want this vision
of a clean energy economy

01:15:09.972 --> 01:15:12.041
and a future
that benefits all.

01:15:12.041 --> 01:15:15.878
So what we need to do is
galvanize this movement, put
pressure on our political

01:15:15.878 --> 01:15:20.683
leaders to do what we want
them to do, to live up to
their responsibility to us,

01:15:21.317 --> 01:15:23.719
to our children and
our grandchildren.

01:15:23.719 --> 01:15:26.922
GROUP: Our future!
Our planet!
Our future!

